Well, today I'm flying this plane.
The first complaint: we need a cute flight log book. Black is too boring, and pink is not pink at all—it's salmon red.
I've always wanted to fly.
Today my dream came true... I actually flew a plane today. I haven't even recovered from the shock yet.
flightaware data.
I was planning to go try again on Saturday. The weather doesn't look good now, but today is Monday.
It seems the challenges in this area are starting to show. Due to the FAA's position on certain medications, I might have a hard time getting my medical certificate.
This isn't impossible, but it will take a lot of time and involve a lot of extra work.
Although this is a bit frustrating, it's just another problem to solve, and it seems "definitely" solvable for now. It just requires a lot of time and money.
If you want to know what challenges I'm facing next:
The FAA doesn't like ADHD. If you're taking medication for ADHD, you definitely won't get your medical certificate.
https://youtu.be/W5JSfq6LLAU?si=xIxPaY8ayqqNSj4c
If I ever have the opportunity to customize the tail number of a plane, it has to be some variant of N1337_, where _ represents any available letter character.
Of course, the sun will still rise when I'm not around, haha. What a letdown.
I'll have to fly again. But this weather is just not cooperating.
Welcome to the world of general aviation! 😜
Based on the ads YouTube thinks I should see, the videos it recommends to me, and the comments, I feel airlines tend to be conservative in tracking.
If the weather allows, I'll fly again on Saturday.
Also, I found a pink flight log book.
Good morning Saturday. I did this today ^_^
#TeaganAir
The flight log book has officially been put into use. I now have 2.3 hours of flight time recorded ^_^
#TeaganAir
If I were to describe what it feels like to fly a small plane, I would say it's like driving a motorcycle/ATV and boat hybrid at 4,000 feet in the air.
On the ground, things change in an instant. The ground has a certain degree of instability, so a motorcycle/ATV is needed.
Also, you might not know that when flying on the ground, you use your feet to control the direction, not the control stick. You use the rudder pedals and brakes. It's not like driving a car.
When flying in the air, you will feel bumps and shakes, and it feels like sailing on water. Although you can control the plane, sometimes the air currents can make you feel a bit dizzy, so you need to adapt to flying in the air, just like a sailor adapts to sailing.
As for this, there's also a random little tidbit:
Flight is very physically demanding. My back and legs are really sore today, feeling like I just went to the gym.
This is not as simple as driving out for a Sunday drive. In my eyes, as a beginner, it's more like a sport than a cruise.
Dear friends, Happy Saturday. Welcome to 4,000 feet in the air.
I will fly again tomorrow, and we will practice stalls and slow flight.
The weather today was unstable, but super fun. We practiced slow flight and stalls. Our ground speed dropped as low as 16 miles per hour, while our airspeed was still at 65 miles per hour.
The weather was clear today, and although there was some fog in the high altitude, the visibility was still great.
